[1]
Date: Thu 7 Aug 2014
Source: Montgomery Advertiser [edited]
http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/news/local/progress-millbrook/2014/08/07/state-health-officials-investigate-legionella-outbreak/13742815/


State public health officials are investigating an outbreak in which people have become ill after being exposed to _Legionella_ bacteria.

A group of about 40 adults and young people from North Alabama might have been exposed to the bacteria in early July 2014 during a series of softball tournaments, said Dr. Mary G. McIntyre with the Alabama Department of Public Health (ADPH). She serves as assistant state health officer for disease control and prevention and epidemiologist for the ADPH.

The exposure likely occurred on or about 12 Jul 2014, with the Health Department receiving the 1st reports on 16 Jul 2014, she said. The group had traveled to softball tournaments in Gadsden, Millbrook and Birmingham, she said.

"We are working now to determine the common factor in the outbreak," she said. "We are conducting environmental investigations at places where the group visited or had in common. At this time, those reports have not been completed, so we do not know the source of the bacteria."

Out of the group, 16 people reported being sickened, she said. Specimens were taken, and 3 people tested positive for being exposed to the _Legionella_ bacteria.

Of those who reported symptoms, one person developed pneumonia and one or 2 people were hospitalized, she said.

The _Legionella_ bacteria grow in warm water and are most often found in large plumbing systems, decorative fountains, hot tubs and cooling towers, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's website. People become infected when they breathe in the bacteria, as they are carried in a mist or vapor. The bacteria can't be spread person to person, according to the CDC.

Symptoms include respiratory distress such as coughing and shortness of breath, mid- to high-level fever, nausea, gastric distress and, in advanced cases, pneumonia, according to the CDC.

_Legionella_ bacteria can cause Legionnaires' disease and Pontiac fever, a less severe sickness than Legionnaires' [disease].

Once the source for the Alabama exposure is determined, steps will be taken to remove the bacteria, McIntyre said.

