[Out of a group of about 40 adults and children from northern Alabama who were on a tour of softball tournaments in the cities of Gadsden, Millbrook and Birmingham in the US state of Alabama, 14 or 16 adults and children (the total varies in the 2 news reports above) reported being sickened with fever, cough and congestion, nausea, vomiting and diarrhea, and one had pneumonia; 3 people tested positive for legionellosis, but we are not told what type of diagnostic tests were done (such as culture, urinary antigen, or serology). We are also not given the timeline over which the cases occurred, nor the age distribution of cases. The suspected source is a hotel in Elmore County, Alabama.

Legionellosis is an infectious disease caused by _Legionella_, most often_Legionella pneumophila_, a Gram-negative bacillus. Legionnaires' disease is the acute pneumonic form of legionellosis, and Pontiac fever is a less severe, non-pneumonic form. Presumably, those sickened in the Alabama outbreak without pneumonia had Pontiac fever.

Legionnaires' disease, and presumably Pontiac fever, are usually acquired by inhalation of an infectious dose of aerosolized _Legionella_. Pontiac fever develops in a very high proportion of people hours to a few days after exposure to a common source, with fever, malaise and muscle aches, whereas Legionnaires' disease has a much lower attack rate and an incubation period of 2 to 14 days after exposure (http://www.cdc.gov/legionella/clinicians.html).

While _Legionella_ can be isolated from respiratory secretions in patients with Legionnaires' disease, _Legionella_ are virtually never isolated from patients with Pontiac fever (http://www.cdc.gov/legionella/top10.htm), and tests for urinary _Legionella_ antigen, which are usually positive in patients with Legionnaires' disease caused by _L. pneumophila_ serogroup 1, may be negative in patients with Pontiac fever (http://cid.oxfordjournals.org/content/44/2/229.full).

The diagnosis of Pontiac fever is usually confirmed by development of antibodies to the _Legionella_ isolated from an environmental source in a significant fraction of affected people exposed to the suspected source. Similarly, the diagnosis of Legionnaires' disease can also be confirmed by the development of antibodies to the _Legionella_ isolated from an environmental source.

Legionnaires' disease attacks more frequently and is more severe in individuals who are elderly, smokers, alcoholics, or who have an underlying illness such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), or a weakened immune system as a result of, for example, organ transplant or taking immunosuppressive drugs (such as corticosteroid therapy) for other reasons. However, healthy individuals can also be at risk of contracting this disease. Legionnaires' disease is uncommon in children, and infected children have usually similar risk factors for legionellosis as have adults, such as heart or lung disease and immunosuppression.

More information concerning the clinical and epidemiological findings in this outbreak would be appreciated from knowledgeable sources.

The city of Millbrook is located in part in Elmore County in the center of the US state of Alabama. Gadsden is about 140 miles (225 km) to the northeast and Birmingham 85 miles (137 km) to the northwest of Millbrook by car. For a map of Alabama that shows the location of these cities, see http://geology.com/cities-map/alabama.shtml. - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2675476,205.]
